  "prompt": "What should you do if you eat undercooked chicken?",
  "response": "If you suspect that you've eaten undercooked chicken, it\u2019s important to take certain steps to minimize the risk of foodborne illness. Here\u2019s what you should do:\n\n1. **Stay Hydrated**: Drink plenty of fluids to stay hydrated, especially if you develop symptoms like diarrhea or vomiting.\n\n2. **Monitor Symptoms**: Watch for signs of food poisoning, which may include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal cramps, fever, and weakness.\n\n3. **Seek Medical Attention**: If you experience severe symptoms or if symptoms persist for more than a couple of days, seek medical advice. Vulnerable groups such as the elderly, young children, pregnant women, and those with weakened immune systems should seek medical attention sooner.\n\n4. **Rest**: Get plenty of rest to help your body recover.\n\n5. **Avoid Anti-Diarrheal Medications**: Unless advised by a healthcare professional, avoid anti-diarrheal medications, as they can sometimes make the infection worse.\n\nPreventative measures for next time include:\n- Cooking chicken to an internal temperature of at least 165\u00b0F (74\u00b0C).\n- Using a meat thermometer to ensure it reaches the correct temperature.\n- Avoiding cross-contamination by using separate cutting boards and utensils for raw chicken and other foods.\n\nIf you have any concerns or if symptoms worsen, contacting a healthcare provider is advised.",
